In [5]:
# Fill missing values (if any) with appropriate methods
# For simplicity, fill numerical columns with the median and categorical columns with the mode
for column in df.columns:
    if df[column].dtype == 'object':
        df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].mode()[0])
    else:
        df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].median())

# Convert subscription_age to a categorical feature (e.g., new, moderate, long-term)
bins = [0, 12, 24, 36, 48, 60, float('inf')]
labels = ['0-1 year', '1-2 years', '2-3 years', '3-4 years', '4-5 years', '5+ years']
df['subscription_age_group'] = pd.cut(df['subscription_age'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

Implement the Feature Engineering:

In [28]:
# Define thresholds based on data analysis
threshold_download = 1000  # Example threshold for heavy users
threshold_upload = 500     # Example threshold for heavy users
threshold_failure_count = 3  # Example threshold for service issues

# Create new features
df['is_heavy_user'] = (df['download_avg'] > threshold_download) & (df['upload_avg'] > threshold_upload)
df['has_service_issues'] = df['service_failure_count'] > threshold_failure_count

# Create age group features
df['subscription_age_group_1-2 years'] = (df['subscription_age'] >= 1) & (df['subscription_age'] < 2)
df['subscription_age_group_2-3 years'] = (df['subscription_age'] >= 2) & (df['subscription_age'] < 3)
df['subscription_age_group_3-4 years'] = (df['subscription_age'] >= 3) & (df['subscription_age'] < 4)
df['subscription_age_group_4-5 years'] = (df['subscription_age'] >= 4) & (df['subscription_age'] < 5)
df['subscription_age_group_5+ years'] = df['subscription_age'] >= 5

# Create a message for missing values
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
missing_values = df.isnull().sum()
if missing_values[missing_values > 0].empty:
    plt.text(0.5, 0.5, 'No Missing Values', horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='center', fontsize=12, color='green')
    plt.axis('off')
else:
    missing_values[missing_values > 0].plot(kind='bar', color='red')
    plt.title('Missing Values')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

# Function to check distribution of categorical columns
def check_categorical_imbalances(dataframe):
    categorical_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns
    for column in categorical_columns:
        print(f"\nDistribution of {column}:")
        print(dataframe[column].value_counts(normalize=True))

from collections import Counter
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\USER\\Downloads\\transformed_internet_service_churn.csv")

# Display the first few rows
print(df.head())

# Checking distribution of 'churn'
print("Distribution of 'churn':")
print(df['churn'].value_counts(normalize=True))

# Checking distribution of other categorical variables
categorical_columns = ['is_tv_subscriber', 'is_movie_package_subscriber', 'is_heavy_user', 'has_service_issues']
for col in categorical_columns:
    print(f"\nDistribution of '{col}':")
    print(df[col].value_counts(normalize=True))

# Separate features and target variable
X = df.drop(columns=['churn'])
y = df['churn']

# Checking original target distribution
print('Original target distribution:', Counter(y))

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Checking new target distribution
print('Resampled target distribution:', Counter(y_resampled))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Plot the distribution of the target variable
target_distribution = df['churn'].value_counts()
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
target_distribution.plot(kind='bar', color=['skyblue', 'salmon'])
plt.title('Distribution of Target Variable (churn)')
plt.xlabel('Churn')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(ticks=[0, 1], labels=['Not Churned (0)', 'Churned (1)'], rotation=0)
plt.show()

The distribution plot of the target variable churn shows the following:

Churned (1): The plot reveals the frequency of churned customers, indicating a significant number of observations in this category. Non-Churned (0): The plot also displays the count of non-churned customers, which is noticeably lower compared to the churned category. Overall, the distribution plot visually confirms that the dataset has a higher frequency of churned customers compared to non-churned ones, illustrating the imbalance in the target variable.

This pie chart highlights a slightly higher proportion of churned customers compared to non-churned ones, reflecting the overall balance of the dataset where churned customers slightly outweigh the non-churned ones.

    plt.show()
